title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine, Quality HMC, 1-44
postcontent:
Probably the nicest M1 Carbine I've come across. Quality Hardware and Machine Corporation SN 4814957, with an Underwood Barrel dated 1-44. Type I carbine, (no bayonet lug, flip rear sight) with everything looking 'right' on it. There are no re-import marks on this one at all. This one was in our hands going to and coming home from the war.

The Receiver is a Type IB, with the detachable operating spring housing ('Q' marked) & a through-drilled operating slide stop hole. The rear sight is marked 'B-Q' and is well-staked on both sides of the pin that the sight pivots on. 

The barrel is an Underwood Type I dated 1-44 and has a long skirt; it has the large 'flaming bomb' ordnance mark, and has a strong 'P' proof mark about 6" from the muzzle. The crown is the original rounded one, and is in good shape, as is the rifling. Bore is shiny, with no visible pitting or damage to my eye.

Bolt is an 'EM-Q' marked type III with a type III firing pin, extractor, and extractor plunger (by serial number range...I can't find my bolt tool to disassemble it). The operating slide is a type IV, marked 'UN-Q' with an '11' stamped on it near the manufacturer mark.

The trigger housing is pretty neat; it is the Type IV style, which was developed by Underwood and made out of sheet steel, which was stamped out, then brazed together, then milled out and various other pieces (trigger guard, etc.) were welded to it to complete it. 'Q-TX' marks it, and it has a type II trigger ('LT-Q'), type II sear ('GE-Q'), type III hammer ('LT-Q'), type III safety (unmarked push button style), and a type IIA magazine catch marked 'EP-Q'. I verified that it is a type IIA by checking the rails; they are 0.10" wide and have no play in the housing (its not a modified Type III with the markings ground off; they have a rail that is 0.070" thick and wobble in the housing)

The stock is a type II, with an oval cut for the oiler. It is a high-wood stock with VERY nice grain around the op handle, but it has a few dings (who wouldn't after being around 67 years?) and it appears that someone marked it with an 'M' or 'W' right behind the recoil plate screw. The 1/2" ordnance cartouche is very clear, about an inch in front of the oiler cutout. The sling is not correct for the gun; its a standard GI-style loop sling, with the hook cut down to fit in the narrower Type IB sling swivel slot.

It will come with 1 Type I 15 round magazine, stamped 'IA'. Magazine is in good shape, for a WWII veteran. Bluing looks good.

I had two gunsmiths look at it, and they both said that the metal was between 95 and 98%, with the bluing wear on the bolt being the biggest issue. They also said it was great wood, but the dings and 'M' ('W'?) hurt it a little; they put the wood at 90 to 95%. At 98%, a Quality HMC carbine with no re-import marks Blue Books at $1675. 95% brings $1250.

This is a 95% gun. The only things that hurt it, in my opinion, is the 'M' carved in the stock (only because I don't know the source...if it was documented to be an initial of a soldier that carried it...wow.) and the sling. The bluing wear on the bolt is nothing unusual, and I'd even say it isn't excessive for its age. I'm asking $1200 for this one. No trades at this time, unless you've got a decent AR (no frankenguns, please) you'd be willing to part with. Cheap ARs and $$$ would be considered.  I'd prefer FTF in the Greensboro, NC area, but can ship on your dime.  I'd have to get your location to work up S&H.

Email me with any questions. I've got tons of pics from the teardown to send if you're interested, and I'll get back to you ASAP.
